:::info
The command creates a new namespaces, and deploys the Stack Automation management server in it. It might take up to 2 minutes for the Management Server to get up and running, so want for the Stack Automation self-service indication to make sure the management server is connected.

1. Now, it's associate our newly connected management server with our space. Click the "Associate to space".
2. The space is already selected for you, but, you still need to set the default namespace and service-account that will be used by Stack Automation to deploy workloads into the cluster. It's always possible to change the default values in the "Administration" section under the "Management Servers" section.
:::

## Step #4: Launch a Deployment

 🚀🚀 Congrats! you are finally now ready to launch your first deployment!  🚀🚀

1. To expose the new blueprint into the __Space catalog__, navigate into the __Blueprints__ page and toggle the  __Publish__ option.
2. Navigate to the __Catalog__ and click the __Launch__ button on the blueprint card.
3. Specify the deployment's name, duration, tags and inputs - note that some of the inputs may be the authentication information required for AWS or Azure as describes in step #3.
4. Optionally assign collaborators to the deployment. While everyone in the space has "read" permission to its deployments, only the deployment's owner and collaborators can perform actions that change the deployment: extend end the deployment, reconcile or update resource changes, etc. When launching the deployment, the new owner/collaborators will receive a notification email if you have [Notifications](/admin-guide/notifications) configured in the space.
5. Finally, click __Launch__.
6. Wait until the deployment is active and use as needed. URLs to the deployment's applications are typically provided as outputs - these can be found in the deployment's __Quicklinks__ on the right pane.
7. Check out the __Resources__ pane to get details about your deployment's resources. Use this tab to understand what assets each grain spun up, get connection details to specific resources, and more.
